Recommended Study Order
The smartest way to attack this list is to follow patterns, not problem count. Start with Arrays/Strings + Two Pointers for weeks 1-2 since these build foundational instincts and appear in nearly every interview. Then move to HashMap, Linked List, Stack/Queue in week 3 — these often appear as "easy" warm-up problems before harder questions. In weeks 4-5, tackle Trees and Recursion since they unlock graph and DP intuition. Spend weeks 6-7 on Graphs and BFS/DFS, then dedicate weeks 8-9 to Dynamic Programming, which is the highest-yield topic for senior roles. Finish with Backtracking, Trie, and Heap in week 10. Always solve 2-3 problems per pattern before moving on — pattern recognition matters more than problem count.
Practice Strategy
For each problem, follow this loop: read the problem, think for 15 minutes without looking at solutions, code it out, test edge cases, then look at the optimal solution and learn the pattern. After solving, write a one-line summary like "Two Sum → HashMap for O(n) lookup" so you can recall patterns quickly later. Revisit problems weekly using spaced repetition — solving a problem twice with a 3-day gap cements it better than solving 3 new ones.
